# Documentation Workflow

Documentation is the primary engineering artifact.

Implementation follows documented intent.

Permanent project knowledge must be recorded in the repository.

---

# Documentation Responsibilities

Each document has a single responsibility.

| Document          | Responsibility                                         |
| ----------------- | ------------------------------------------------------ |
| `PROJECT.md`      | Project vision, goals, scope and MVP                   |
| `ROADMAP.md`      | Long-term implementation strategy                      |
| `ARCHITECTURE.md` | System organization and architectural boundaries       |
| `ENGINEERING.md`  | Engineering decisions, tooling and project conventions |
| ADRs              | Significant architectural decisions                    |
| Plans             | Authorized implementation increments                   |
| `PROGRESS.md`     | Completed engineering history                          |
| `RUNBOOK.md`      | Operational procedures                                 |

Avoid duplicating information across documents.

Every piece of knowledge should have one authoritative location.

---

# Documentation Lifecycle

Project knowledge matures through the following lifecycle:

```text
Idea
        ↓
PROJECT.md
        ↓
ROADMAP.md
        ↓
ARCHITECTURE.md
        ↓
ENGINEERING.md
        ↓
Repository Initialization
        ↓
Implementation Plan
        ↓
Implementation
        ↓
Code Review
        ↓
PROGRESS.md
```

Architecture decisions should be recorded as ADRs whenever appropriate.

---

# Documentation Updates

Update documentation whenever:

* project goals change;
* roadmap changes;
* architecture changes;
* engineering decisions change;
* repository structure changes;
* operational procedures change;
* new durable project knowledge appears.

Do not leave important decisions only in chat history.

---

# Engineering Decisions

`ENGINEERING.md` records project-specific engineering decisions.

Examples include:

* language and runtime versions;
* dependency management;
* quality tooling;
* repository layout;
* validation commands;
* testing strategy;
* configuration strategy;
* operational assumptions.

Do not duplicate architectural decisions in `ENGINEERING.md`.

---

# Architectural Decisions

Create or update an ADR when a decision:

* changes architectural boundaries;
* introduces a long-term architectural pattern;
* changes integration strategy;
* establishes an important architectural convention;
* is difficult or costly to reverse.

Do not create ADRs for ordinary implementation details.

---

# Progress Tracking

`PROGRESS.md` records completed work only.

Record:

* completed implementation increments;
* engineering milestones;
* important artifacts;
* completed architectural or engineering work.

Do not record:

* future work;
* TODO lists;
* implementation ideas.

---

# Documentation Consistency

Repository documentation should remain internally consistent.

When updating one document, verify whether related documents also require updates.

Typical examples:

* `PROJECT.md` → `ROADMAP.md`
* `ROADMAP.md` → implementation plans
* `ARCHITECTURE.md` → ADRs
* `ENGINEERING.md` → `RUNBOOK.md`
* completed plans → `PROGRESS.md`

---

# Repository Knowledge Rule

Promote durable knowledge into the repository.

Examples include:

* engineering decisions;
* architectural rules;
* project conventions;
* repeatable workflows;
* implementation strategies;
* operational procedures.

Do not rely on conversational memory.

---

# General Rule

Documentation drives implementation.

Implementation should never become the only source of project knowledge.

Repository knowledge should remain explicit, discoverable, and consistent throughout the project lifecycle.
